definitionExtended:
Inpatient days should exclusively be based on the midnight census, not on admissions or other administrative procedures. The following rules apply:
A patient discharged on the day following the date of admission has a stay of 1 (one) patient day. A patient discharged 2 (two) days after the date of admission (e.g. admitted on Tuesday and discharged on Thursday) has a stay of 2 (two) patient days. We encourage hospitals to collect all specialities, including TB and step down, in their respective hospitals to calculate the total inpatient days. Patients that are discharged but should be accommodated by the hospital due to the unavailability of immediate transport should not be admitted as an inpatient but as a lodger unless the condition of the client warrants an admission. If a patient is scheduled for an OPD visit at another hospital and has to wait for some time at the hospital for transport reasons, the patient should not be admitted as an inpatient but as a boarder unless the condition of the client warrants an admission.
 Boarder criteria:
The person should occupy a bed;
The person should receive meals;
The person should have access to bathroom facilities

